<br>
There is value in utility spells.  Verant has mentioned utility spells more than once as a reason not to upgrade caster damage, and why they think balancing casters is harder than melee.  I'm starting to agree with them.  What value do you place on an invisibility spell, or sow?  They might both save your bacon, in any given situation.  They obviously have some value, but how much?  Can you really negate that value and call a warrior balanced if their is an item in the game that has a right click invis effect?  I don't have that item!  What about me?  How do you balance the game with items?  Especially in a game where some items are so hard to get, requiring inordinate amounts of time and effort.  Time might just be the only measurement we have to apply to utility spells.  Then must we convert our time value into part of the damage balance equation?<br>
<br>
How much time does having sow save you, or teleport?  Compare that to the downtime a warrior experiences by not having these things.  How much would a warrior pay for a teleport across norrath saving him an hour long CR, or the invis to reach his corpse in a dungeon?  It's pretty much a given that a warrior is practically defenseless without his gear.  How much time does having your spells back right away save you on a CR?  Should that, and utility spells be taken into account when discussing balance?  I think it should.  To what degree do utility spells factor into the balance equation?  To what degree does gettting your spells back right away upon death factor in?  The ability to bind anywhere saving you a long CR?  I know that warriors also benefit from these spells, but only when they are given to them.  Perhaps that lessens the value we should place on them considering balance between casters and melee.  <br>
<br>
Then we could take it a step further and consider AC.  If a Wizard gets aggro he's dead meat.  Wizards give up a lot of defense for the offense they are supposed to have.  Do they have it?  Perhaps not, but then they aren't supposed to take hits from a mob, so how much damage is appropriate?  It's a hard question to answer.  Should it be more than a warrior?  Well you can read above, and see that there appear to be a lot of variables to consider.  I guess you just have to go with what feels right.<br>
<br>
Balance can also be viewed from several perspectives.  There's PvP, group desirability, and soloability.  I think nobody would argue the wizard is a far better solo class at higher levels.  Should this also factor into the balance equation, or should it be dismissed, since this is a grouping game?  Do you approach balance from all three angles and then take the average, or do you weight one more heavily than the other?  The more I think about it the more I am awed by the tremendous undertaking that is class balance!  Perhaps Verant isn't doing such a bad job after all.... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 3581<br> <font color=#ffffff>(10/30/01 3:08 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: My eyes have been opened!</span><hr size=1> &quot;It seems like what some of you are saying that if there were items available that could twink a wizard as effectively as a warrior you would consider yourselves balanced.&quot;<br>
